\begin_layout Standard
In this experiment a wide range of standard classifiers are applied to both
 the balanced and unbalanced datasets using n-gram range of unigrams, bigrams
 and trigrams where the n-gram range of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 degree is a combination of all lower n-grams starting from unigrams, bigrams
 till the degree N.
 For example the trigram range is a combination of unigrams, bigrams and
 trigrams.
 Also the experiment is applied on the Tf-Idf 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:tfidf"

\end_inset

 (token frequency inverse document frequency) of the n-grams.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Experiment-2:-Polarity"

\end_inset

 shows the result for each classifier on the test set where the performance
 measures are weighted F1 measure and total accuracy.
 Note that the inclusion of a third class "neutral" makes the problem much
 harder, and we get a lower performance than the case of two-class case
 ("positive" and "negative").
 The reason is that there is a large confusion between neutral and positive,
 and between neutral and negative.
 Sometimes the numbered ratings (1 to 5), from which we extract the target
 class contradict what is written in the review, that even an experienced
 human analyzer will not get it right.
 Two accuracy measures are used to calculate the performance which are the
 total accuracy
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1"

\end_inset

 and weighted F1 measure
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2"

\end_inset

.
