\begin_layout Standard
The classifiers used in this experiment are widely used in the area of sentiment
 analysis and can be considered as a baseline for any further experiments.
 The classifiers used are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Multinomial Naive Bayes: 
\series default
A well known method that is used in most NLP tasks.
 In this method each review is represented as a bag of words 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}=<x_{1},x_{2}...,x_{n}>$
\end_inset

 where the feature values are the term frequencies then the Bayes rule can
 be applied to form a linear classifier.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
log(\, p(class|\bar{X})\,)=log(\, p(class)\,*\prod_{i=1}^{n}p(\, x_{i}|class\,))
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
log(\, p(class|\bar{X})\,)=log(\, p(class)\,)+\sum_{i=1}^{n}log(p(\, x_{i}|class\,))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Bernoulli Naive Bayes: 
\series default
In this model
\series bold
 
\series default
features are independent binary variables that describe the input 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}=<1,0,1...1>$
\end_inset

, which means the binary term occurrence is used instead of the frequency
 of the term in the bag of words model.
 the likelihood of a review given a class c is: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(class|\bar{X})=\prod_{i=1}^{n}[\: p(token_{i}|class)^{x_{i}}*(1-p(token_{i}|class))^{1-x_{i}}\:]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Support Vector Machine: 
\series default
Linear SVM is a classifier that partitions the data using the linear formula
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\bar{W}\,.\,\bar{X}+p$
\end_inset

, selected in such a way that it maximizes the margin of separation between
 the decision boundary and the class patterns (hence the name large margin
 classifier).
 SVM can be generalized to multiclass case using one versus all classification
 trick.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Passive Aggressive:
\series default
 It is an online learning model that uses a hinge-loss function together
 with an aggressiveness parameter C, in order to achieve a postive margin
 high confidence classifier.
 The algorithm is described in details in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "crammer2006online"

\end_inset


\series bold
 
\series default
with two alternative modifications that make the algorithm's ability to
 cope with noise better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Stochastic Gradient Descent: 
\series default
It is an algorithm that is used to train other machine learning algorithms
 such as SVM where it samples a subset of training examples at every learning
 step.
 Then it calculates the gradient from this subset only, and uses the gradient
 to update the weight vector w in case of SVM classifier.
 It is widely used in case of large-scale machine learning problems
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bottou2007tradeoffs"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Logistic Regression: 
\series default
The logistic regression uses a sigmoid function 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{w}(x)=f(x)=\frac{1}{1+e^{-w^{T}x}}$
\end_inset

 as a learning model, then it optimizes a cost function that measures the
 likelihood of the data given the classifier's class probability estimates.
 The cost function can be formulated as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Cost(\bar{w})=\frac{-1}{m}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\:[y^{(i)}log(h_{w}(x^{(i)}))+(1-y^{(i)})log(1-h_{w}(x^{(i)}))]
\]

\end_inset

 where m is the total nuber of patterns, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{(i)}$
\end_inset

is the pattern i and 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{(i)}$
\end_inset

 is the correct class of the pattern i.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Perceptron: 
\series default
It is a simple feed-forward single layer linear neural network with a unit
 step function as an activation function.
 It uses an iterative algorithm for training the weights, but that algorithm
 does not take into account the margin..
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
K-Nearest Neighbour:
\series default
 A simple well-known machine learning classifier based on distances between
 the patterns in the feature space.
 Specifically, a pattern is classified according to the majority class of
 its K-nearest neighbours.
 
