 There are two overriding reasons why one should consider applying feature
 selection.
 The first reason is that with such large number of features the classifier
 can exhibit some overfitting, due to the curse of dimensionality.
 The other reason is that with millions of features, the computational burden
 will be too high for many classifiersto be practically feasible.
 This will basically exclude many good classifiers that have the potential
 to improve the performance.
 In this experiment we test whether any of these two arguments are valid,
 and explore whether feature selection is beneficial.
 So some feature selection techniques were applied to Tf-Idf (token frequency
 inverse document frequency) trigram training set to explore their effects.
 The feature selection experiments are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
SVM (l1 loss) classifier:
\series default
 One of the beneficial features of the linear SVM is that inherently applies
 some sort of feature selection.
 This is because the weight values are an indication of the importance of
 the features.
 For example, features that have negligible corresponding weights are deemed
 unimportant or ineffective.
 This is especially true if we use the L1 error measure for training the
 SVM (defined as norm 
\begin_inset Formula $||x||_{1}=\sum_{i}|x_{i}|$
\end_inset

).
 In such case, many insignificant weight will end up being zero.
 So, we utilize this aspect to perform feature selection using L1 SVM training.
 We sort the features by decreasing weights, and keep the K features with
 the highest 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 features.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Logistic regression classifier:
\series default
 Similar to the case of SVM, logistic regression performs some form of inherent
 feature selection.
 We therefore utilize the logistic regression as a tool for selecting the
 top features, associated with the largest weights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Chi-squared feature selection: 
\series default
A well known method that is used to test the independence of two events,
 and that is based on the identity that defines independent events A and
 B as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(AB)=P(A)*P(B)
\]

\end_inset

In NLP feature selection, event A is the occurrence of the class and event
 B is the occurrence of term.
 Then terms are ranked according to the following formula: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X^{2}(D,t,c)=\sum_{e_{t}\text{Є\{0,1\}}}\sum_{e_{c}\text{Є\{0,1\}}}\frac{(N_{e_{t}e_{c}}-E_{e_{t}e_{c}})^{2}}{E_{e_{t}e_{c}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
where e
\begin_inset Formula $_{t}$
\end_inset

 means whether the document contains term t or not, e
\begin_inset Formula $_{c}$
\end_inset

 means whether the document is in class c or not, N is the count of documents
 D that have the values of e
\begin_inset Formula $_{t}$
\end_inset

and e
\begin_inset Formula $_{c}$
\end_inset

 that are indicated by the two subscripts, and E is the expected frequency.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Analysis of variance feature selection:
\series default
 The ANOVA F-test can be used to assess the weight of each feature in a
 data set.
 The formula for the ANOVA F-test statistic is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\frac{Explained\, Variance}{Un\, Explained\, Variance}
\]

\end_inset

where the explained variance is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}\frac{n_{i}(\overline{Y}_{i}-\overline{Y})^{2}}{K-1}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{Y}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the sample mean in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 feature, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the number of observations in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{th}$
\end_inset

 feature, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{Y}$
\end_inset

 is the overall mean of the data, and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is total the number of features.
 The unexplained variance is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{ij}\frac{n_{i}(Y_{ij}-\overline{Y})^{2}}{N-K}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 observation in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 feature, 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is total the number of features, and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the overall sample size.
 Then, the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 value based on the 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 statistic is calculated by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
pvalue=Prob\:{F(K-1,N-K)>F}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $F(K-1,N-K)$
\end_inset

 is a random variable that follows an 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 distribution with degree of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $K-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N-K$
\end_inset

 predictors are ranked by sorting according to the 
\begin_inset Formula $pvalue$
\end_inset

 in ascending order.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Relief feature selection: 
\series default
Relief is a scoring feature selection algorithm based on nearest neighbours.
 The Relief algorithm will be repeated 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 times to adjust the weights of the features by selecting a random instance
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 from the data every iteration as follow
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{i}=W_{i-1}-(x_{i}-nearHit_{i})^{2}+\sum_{c}(x_{i}-nearMiss_{i,c})^{2}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the feature vector weight at iteration 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
